    cy.get('some-element').should('exist'); // Ensure element exists
    // Example screenshot:
    cy.get('#example-id').as('elementId');
    cy.get('@elementId').then(($el) => {
      $el.screenshot('./screenshots/some_element.png');
    });
  });

  it('should handle errors gracefully', () => {
    // Add error handling and screen shot logic here
  });
});
```

### Step 6: Running Tests

To run your tests, navigate to the root of your project directory in your terminal and execute:

```bash
npx cypress open
```

Your tests should now be set up to automatically capture screenshots when they fail or pass. The screenshots will be stored in the `./screenshots` folder within your project.

### Conclusion

By following these steps, you've created a robust Cypress testing framework that includes automatic screenshot capture and saving capabilities. This can significantly enhance the visibility and debugging of your tests, especially in complex UI scenarios.

